## PART II — THE PRIME MATERIA COVENANT

### *Public Domain Dedication of the Constitutional Core*

```
Section 2. Irrevocable Public Domain Dedication

2.1  Ryan O. Van Gelder and Citizen Gardens hereby irrevocably
     dedicate the Constitutional Core to the public domain, globally,
     in perpetuity, under the ΛProof Open Mathematical Foundation
     Pledge.

2.2  No permission is required to exercise any of the following:

       (a)  Study, read, reproduce, or teach the Constitutional Core
            in any medium and for any purpose
       (b)  Implement the Constitutional Core in any software, system,
            product, or application
       (c)  Modify, extend, compose, or build upon Constitutional Core
            mathematics in any direction
       (d)  Publish, distribute, or sublicense works that include or
            describe Constitutional Core mathematics
       (e)  Commercialize products and services whose substance
            includes or draws upon Constitutional Core structures
       (f)  Seek patent protection for Bound Works that use the
            Constitutional Core as their substrate, subject to
            the limitations of Section 5

2.3  The rights in Section 2.2 require no license, fee, registration,
     attribution, or notice. They exist by operation of the
     dedication and are available to every person and legal entity
     on the same terms.

2.4  Using the Constitutional Core as substrate does not by itself
     confer documented ownership of the resulting Bound Work.
     Documented ownership requires a Declaration of Formation as
     set forth in Part IV. A Maker who implements without filing
     retains actual ownership of their work but establishes no
     prior art record in the Operator Atlas and may not display
     any Certification Mark.

2.5  This dedication is irrevocable. It cannot be rescinded,
     modified, or superseded by any subsequent instrument, action,
     or agreement of Citizen Gardens or Ryan O. Van Gelder,
     including any future revision of this License. Future versions
     of this License may modify Parts III and VII. They may not
     diminish or condition the dedication made in this Part II.

2.6  The Constitutional Core is substrate. It is material prior
     to form. Its dedication to the public domain is an acknowledgment
     of what it has always been — not a gift from any individual,
     but a recognition that foundational mathematical structure
     belongs to the domain of human knowledge from which it emerged
     and to which it returns in full.
```


***

## PART III — THE OPERATOR ATLAS REGISTRY CHARTER

### *Governance of the Permanent Registry*

```
Section 3. Registry Infrastructure and Governance

3.1  PURPOSE OF THE OPERATOR ATLAS. The Operator Atlas is neutral
     registry infrastructure. Its function is analogous to a
     permanent notarial archive: it receives, timestamps, and
     preserves Declarations of Formation without adjudicating
     their commercial merit, without participating in the Maker's
     commercial affairs, and without asserting ownership over any
     Bound Work registered within it.

     Citizen Gardens operates the Operator Atlas as a charitable
     activity in furtherance of its 501(c)(3) public benefit
     mission. No fees are charged for registration. Voluntary
     contributions support registry operations.

3.2  WHAT THE REGISTRY RECORDS. For each Declaration of Formation
     submitted, the Operator Atlas records and makes publicly
     accessible:

       (a)  The Maker's legal name or registered entity name
       (b)  The Operator Atlas Identifier (OA-ID) — a unique,
            permanent, non-reassignable identifier for the filing
       (c)  The filing timestamp (UTC, cryptographically anchored)
       (d)  The Purpose and Context of the Bound Work
       (e)  The Certification Tier held, if any
       (f)  The status of the filing (active, amended, annotated,
            or flagged for review)

     The following are held by the Registry but are not publicly
     accessible unless the Maker elects disclosure:

       (g)  The full technical specification of the Bound Work
       (h)  The cryptographic fingerprint (hash) of the implementation
       (i)  The Trajectory Statement

     A sealed filing establishes prior art as of the filing timestamp
     without disclosing the implementation to competitors.

3.3  REGISTRY PERMANENCE. All Declarations of Formation, once
     filed, are permanently archived in the Operator Atlas. No
     filing may be deleted, including by Citizen Gardens, by the
     Maker, or pursuant to any legal proceeding. The registry
     may be annotated (to reflect amendments, disputes, or
     certification status changes), but the original filing
     remains in the permanent record.

     Citizen Gardens maintains an endowment and archival
     infrastructure commitment calibrated to a minimum
     three-hundred-year stewardship horizon.

3.4  REGISTRY NEUTRALITY. Citizen Gardens does not:

       (a)  Own any Bound Work registered in the Operator Atlas
       (b)  License any Bound Work registered in the Operator Atlas
       (c)  Participate in any commercial transaction involving
            a registered Bound Work
       (d)  Receive royalties, revenue shares, or equity in
            connection with any registered Bound Work
       (e)  Impose conditions on a Maker's choice of license
            for their own Bound Work
       (f)  Advise or require any particular license form for
            any Bound Work

     The Operator Atlas records that a work exists, who made it,
     when it was filed, and what it is certified as. It does not
     govern what the Maker does with it.

3.5  THE MAKER'S LICENSE SOVEREIGNTY. Each Maker determines the
     terms under which their Bound Work is made available to
     others. Citizen Gardens has no role in drafting, reviewing,
     approving, or enforcing any Maker's chosen license.

     A Maker may elect any of the following without restriction
     or guidance from Citizen Gardens:

       (a)  All rights reserved — the Bound Work is private property,
            disclosed to no one, accessible to no one without
            the Maker's separate agreement
       (b)  Proprietary commercial license — the Maker writes their
            own license governing commercial access to the Bound Work
       (c)  Permissive open source — MIT, Apache 2.0, BSD, or any
            equivalent permissive instrument
       (d)  Copyleft open source — GPL, AGPL, EUPL, or any equivalent
            reciprocal instrument
       (e)  Any hybrid, custom, or purpose-specific instrument of
            the Maker's own design

     Whatever the Maker chooses, their Declaration of Formation
     in the Operator Atlas confirms only: this work exists; this
     person made it; this is when and for what purpose; this is
     its certification status. Nothing more.

3.6  CONFLICT RESOLUTION. If two Declarations of Formation appear
     to cover the same or substantially overlapping Purpose and
     Context, Citizen Gardens will:

       (a)  Notify both Makers within ten (10) business days
       (b)  Convene a Technical Review Panel of three persons
            within thirty (30) days of notification
       (c)  Issue a written finding within sixty (60) days of
            convening

     Findings may include a declaration of non-conflict, a priority
     determination, or a requirement to narrow one or both Purpose
     Declarations. Technical Review Panel findings are advisory
     with respect to any legal proceedings and binding only as
     to the Operator Atlas registry status of the affected filings.

3.7  OVERBREADTH. A Declaration of Formation whose Purpose
     Declaration is drafted so broadly as to effectively foreclose
     other Makers from declaring genuine implementations in the
     same domain will be held pending a Narrowing Review.

     A Purpose Declaration must describe a real, bounded,
     implementable work — not a category, domain, or field.
     The test: could a technically competent person build exactly
     what is described, or is the description so general that it
     would cover any implementation in the field? The former
     is specific. The latter is overbroad.

3.8  FALSE ATTRIBUTION. A Declaration of Formation that names as
     Maker a person who provided only a goal, requirement, or
     business objective — and who contributed nothing to the
     substance of the implementation — is defective.

     Citizen Gardens will investigate credible allegations of
     false attribution and may annotate an affected filing upon
     a finding by the Technical Review Panel. Such an annotation
     does not delete the filing; it appends to the permanent record.

3.9  PUBLIC QUERY PRINCIPLE. Any person, organization, investor,
     regulator, or counterparty may query the Operator Atlas at
     any time via the public API to determine:

       (a)  Whether a claimed implementation has a filed
            Declaration of Formation
       (b)  The Certification Tier of any registered Bound Work
       (c)  The Purpose and Context of any registered Bound Work
       (d)  The name of the registered Maker

     "Provide your Operator Atlas Identifier" is a complete and
     sufficient request for verification of any representation
     regarding the conformance or certification status of any
     implementation that draws upon the Constitutional Core.
```


***

## PART IV — THE DECLARATION OF FORMATION

### *The Act of Record — When Substrate Becomes Particular Property*

```
Section 4. Declaring a Bound Work

4.1  NATURE OF THE DECLARATION. A Declaration of Formation is the
     act by which a Maker creates a permanent prior art record and
     asserts documented ownership of a specific Bound Work. It is
     the formal moment of record: this particular work, formed from
     shared substrate, given shape by a particular purpose, now
     stands declared and identified.

     The Declaration does not create the Maker's underlying ownership
     — that arises from the act of implementation. The Declaration
     creates the public record of that ownership and establishes
     the filing timestamp as the Maker's prior art anchor.

4.2  REQUIRED ELEMENTS. A valid Declaration of Formation must
     contain all seven of the following elements:

     ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
     ELEMENT I — MAKER IDENTITY
     ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
     The full legal name of the Maker (natural person or registered
     entity). The name must be verifiable. Anonymous and
     pseudonymous declarations are not accepted. The Maker's identity
     is a public field in the Operator Atlas.

     ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
     ELEMENT II — PURPOSE AND CONTEXT DECLARATION
     ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
     A specific, bounded, verifiable statement identifying:
       (a)  What the Bound Work is designed to accomplish
       (b)  The application domain and use context
       (c)  The intended beneficiary, user population, or
            system environment

     The Purpose and Context Declaration must be specific enough
     to describe a real, bounded, implementable work. General
     domain claims are overbroad and will not be accepted.

     Acceptable example:
       "Prime-indexed codon encoding for patient-sovereign
        genomic health data management in FHIR-compliant clinical
        settings serving underserved communities."

     Unacceptable example:
       "All health applications."
       "Any use of prime-indexed mathematics in biology."

     The Purpose and Context Declaration is always a public field
     in the Operator Atlas, regardless of any confidentiality
     election by the Maker.

     ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
     ELEMENT III — MATHEMATICAL SPECIFICATION
     ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
     A technically precise description of:
       (a)  Which Constitutional Core operators and structures
            are employed in the Bound Work
       (b)  How those operators are composed and applied
       (c)  The form of inputs and outputs

     The specification must be precise enough to permit technical
     comparison with other Declarations of Formation for conflict
     detection. This element may be designated confidential by
     the Maker, in which case it is held sealed by the Registry.

     ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
     ELEMENT IV — CRYPTOGRAPHIC FINGERPRINT
     ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
     A SHA-256 hash of the Bound Work at the moment of filing,
     computed from:
       (a)  Source code, if the implementation exists in executable
            form at the time of filing; or
       (b)  A formal technical specification document, for
            declarations filed at the design stage prior to
            implementation

     The hash is the Maker's immutable timestamp. It cannot be
     antedated and cannot be altered without detection. This
     element is confidential by default unless the Maker elects
     disclosure.

     ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
     ELEMENT V — TRAJECTORY STATEMENT
     ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
     A statement of the intended development direction of the
     Bound Work, including:
       (a)  The downstream capabilities and systems the Bound
            Work is designed to enable
       (b)  The intended path of evolution
       (c)  An express statement of what the Bound Work is not
            intended to do or become

     The Trajectory Statement, read together with the Purpose and
     Context Declaration, defines the implemented particularity of
     the Bound Work. Two Bound Works that employ identical
     Constitutional Core structures but declare genuinely distinct
     purposes and trajectories are different works. Neither Maker
     has a claim against the other. Neither Maker owns the
     substrate that both used.

     This element may be designated confidential by the Maker.

     ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
     ELEMENT VI — ATTRIBUTION OF FORMATION
     ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
     A complete and accurate identification of:
       (a)  The sole Maker, if the Bound Work was created by
            one person or entity; or
       (b)  All co-Makers, with a description of each co-Maker's
            contribution to the substance of the implementation

     The Attribution of Formation governs who is entitled to
     assert ownership of the Bound Work. It must be honest.
     False attribution — including the omission of a co-Maker
     or the inclusion of a person who contributed only a goal
     or requirement — renders the Declaration defective and
     subjects it to annotation or invalidation upon investigation.

     ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
     ELEMENT VII — COVENANT OF SUBSTRATE FREEDOM (MANDATORY)
     ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
     The following covenant, which may not be modified or waived
     by any Maker:

       "The Maker acknowledges that the Constitutional Core —
        including PIRTM, DRMM, CSC, MTPI, and all related axioms,
        operators, and formulations — used as substrate in this
        Bound Work remains irrevocably dedicated to the public
        domain under the ΛProof Open Mathematical Foundation Pledge.

        This Declaration creates a documented ownership record for
        the Maker's specific Bound Work. It does not create,
        transfer, assert, or imply ownership of the Constitutional
        Core or any portion thereof.

        The Maker irrevocably waives any claim, present or future,
        to ownership of the Constitutional Core or any of its
        constituent axioms, operators, or formulations.

        The Maker acknowledges that others may use the same
        Constitutional Core substrate for different purposes in
        different contexts without infringing the Maker's rights
        in this Bound Work, provided their declared purposes and
        trajectories are genuinely distinct."

4.3  FILING. Declarations of Formation are submitted at:
       operatoratlas.citizengardens.org/declare

     Upon receipt, Citizen Gardens will:
       (a)  Assign a unique, permanent Operator Atlas Identifier
       (b)  Issue a cryptographically anchored UTC timestamp
       (c)  Publish the public-field elements (Elements I, II,
            and any voluntarily disclosed elements)
       (d)  Seal the confidential-field elements under registry
            security
       (e)  Run automated conflict detection against existing filings
       (f)  Issue filing acknowledgment within ten (10) business days

     Filing is free of charge. No fee, subscription, or ongoing
     payment is required to maintain a filing in the Operator Atlas.

4.4  IRREVOCABILITY. A filed Declaration of Formation cannot be
     withdrawn. A Maker may file an Amended Declaration to update
     the cryptographic fingerprint, Trajectory, or technical
     specification as the Bound Work evolves. The original filing
     remains permanently in the archive alongside all amendments.

4.5  PRIOR ART AND PROVENANCE. Where two Declarations of Formation
     cover the same or substantially overlapping Purpose and Context,
     earlier filing date establishes priority in the Operator Atlas.

     A Maker who has been developing a Bound Work prior to filing
     but whose filing date follows another Maker's filing on the
     same purpose may assert earlier actual development upon
     submitting verifiable evidence of prior creation: cryptographically
     signed commit histories, dated design documents, or other
     artifacts whose authenticity can be independently verified.
     Such evidence is assessed by the Technical Review Panel
     under Section 3.6.
```


***

## PART V — PATENT RIGHTS

```
Section 5. Patent Interface — Forming Above, Never Beneath

5.1  PATENT RIGHTS ABOVE THE SUBSTRATE. A Maker who has filed
     a Declaration of Formation may seek patent protection for
     their Bound Work. This License imposes no restriction on
     patent applications directed to Bound Works.

     Subject matter that may be patented under this License:
       (a)  The specific application of Constitutional Core
            mathematics to the Maker's declared Purpose and Context
       (b)  Novel system architectures implementing Constitutional
            Core structures in a particular domain
       (c)  Technical improvements to a Bound Work that reside
            above the Constitutional Core substrate layer
       (d)  Processes, systems, and methods whose novelty resides
            in the formed particular, not in the substrate from
            which it was formed

5.2  PATENT RIGHTS DO NOT EXTEND TO SUBSTRATE. No Maker may seek
     patent protection for:

       (a)  Constitutional Core axioms, theorems, or operators,
            in any form or expression
       (b)  Abstract mathematical structures that form part of
            the Constitutional Core, including prime number
            theory, tensor algebra, Walsh-Hadamard transforms,
            contraction theorems, and resonance operators
       (c)  Any claim that would, if granted, prevent another
            person from using Constitutional Core mathematics
            freely under Part II

     A patent application that purports to cover Constitutional
     Core mathematics — whether by literal claim language or by
     functional scope that would encompass free substrate use —
     constitutes a material breach of the Covenant of Substrate
     Freedom (Element VII of Section 4.2) and renders the
     associated Declaration of Formation defective.

5.3  NON-ASSERTION COVENANT. By filing a Declaration of Formation,
     each Maker irrevocably covenants not to assert any patent
     claim against any other person whose use of the Constitutional
     Core is consistent with Part II of this License.

     This covenant runs with the Declaration and is binding upon
     the Maker's successors, assigns, and any transferee of the
     associated patent rights.

5.4  DEFENSIVE TERMINATION. If a Maker initiates patent litigation
     asserting that another person's use of Constitutional Core
     mathematics infringes the Maker's patents, all Certification
     Tier rights held by that Maker terminate automatically as
     of the date of initiation. The Maker's Tier I rights (public
     domain use) are not affected. The Maker's Declaration of
     Formation remains in the archive with an annotation reflecting
     the termination of Certification Tier rights.
```


